

<section xml:id="Ch4Sec3DiagonalizingMatricies">
  <title>Diagonalizing matrices</title>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        We say that an <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>\mat{A}</m> is
        <term>diagonalizable</term>
        if there exists an invertible
        <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>\mat{P}</m> such that
        <m>\mat{P}^{-1} \mat{A} \mat{P}</m> is a diagonal matrix.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <m>\mat{A} = \cmatrix{ 2 \amp  1 \\ \frac{1}{2} \amp  \frac{5}{2} }</m> is diagonalizable,
        since if we set
        <md>
          \mat{P} = \cmatrix{-2 \amp  1 \\ 1 \amp  1}
        </md>
        then
        <md>
          \mat{P}^{-1} = -\frac{1}{3} \cmatrix{1 \amp  -1 \\ -1 \amp  -2}
        </md>
        and we check,
        <md>
          <mrow>\mat{P}^{-1} \mat{A} \mat{P} \amp = -\frac{1}{3} {\cmatrix{1 \amp  -1</mrow>
          <mrow>-1 \amp  -2}} {\cmatrix{2 \amp  1</mrow>
          <mrow>\frac{1}{2} \amp  \frac{5}{3}}} {\cmatrix{ -2 \amp  1</mrow>
          <mrow>1 \amp  1}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = - \frac{1}{3} {\cmatrix{ \frac{3}{2} \amp  - \frac{3}{2}</mrow>
          <mrow>-3 \amp  -6}} {\cmatrix{-2 \amp  1</mrow>
          <mrow>1 \amp  1}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = - \frac{1}{3} {\cmatrix{ - \frac{9}{2} \amp  0</mrow>
          <mrow>0 \amp  -9}}</mrow>
          <mrow>= {\cmatrix{\frac{3}{2} \amp  0</mrow>
          <mrow>0 \amp  3}}</mrow>
        </md>
        which is indeed a diagonal matrix.
        More on this in the second semester!
        For now this is all you need to know.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

